full_book_title: Les colloques du calvaire, ou méditations sur la Passion de N. S. Jesus-Christ
notes: Edition not located. Author and superbook attributions after worldcat, which lists 1778 editions by Hovius, St Malo, and another s.l., s.n.. The full title of the latter is 'Les colloques du calvaire, ou méditations sur la Passion de N. S. Jesus-Christ ; en forme d'entretien pour chaque jour du mois : par Mre Courbon, prêtre, docteur en théologie, curé de S. Cyr. Nouvelle édition corrigée, augmentée d'une Pratique pour bien faire ses actions chaque jour de la semaine, avec les prieres du matin, du soir, durant la sainte messe, pour la confession, & la sainte communion, &c. &c.' This could possibly be the edition in question here if document date reads 1778, which is unclear.

full_book_title: De Imitatione JC. [Jesu Christi], libri quatuor
notes: Edition verified through google books edition, which contains the permit dated 7 December 1787. This edition is also in Worldcat, entitled 'De Imitatione Christi, libri quatuor' and dated 1788: this also confirms format and gives Latin publisher details. The BNF notice on the edition reads: 'En fin, table, et permission simple donnant obligation du format, du tirage (1000 ex.) et de "faire ladite édition absolument conforme à celle d'Elzevir", accordée à Paris, le 7 décembre, 1787, et enregistrée à Orléans le 23 décembre 1787).' Jacob would be awarded a further permit in February 1788.  The two should not be confused. The publisher's address is given as ' viâ Sancti Salvatoris'.

full_book_title: Entretien (l') de Jésus au très saint sacrement de l'autel
notes: Edition not located; superbook attribution almost certain but differs from Dawson. Uncharacteristically, Dawson overlooks the all but perfect title match between the source data and Dusault's, 'Entretiens avec Jésus-Christ dans le très Saint Sacrement de l’Autel’, even though he identifies this work from a short title elsewhere in the permission simple register. Dusault's entretiens ran through multiple known editions from 1701-1777 and again from 1829.  Dawson's alternative and tentative suggestion that this could be Jean Crasset 'Entretien de devotion sur le saint sacrement de l'autel' looks highly improbable and workdcat lists no editions between 1721 and a revival of interest in the nineteenth century.

full_book_title: Heures dédiées au roi contenant les prières du matin, etc
notes: Superbook and edition not identified.  Worldcat lists c17 edition with longer title. In the source data, this entry names two publishers. The other is Monnoyer père in Neufchâteau. On this item the name of Le Seure appears first in the source data, some of which appears to be added after it was first written. The relevant part of the entry  reads 'Le Seure l'aine, imp. a Nancy, Monnoyer Libre Imp [Libraire Imprimeur] a Neufchateau'. Dawson assumed that two licences were granted the same day, but it seems more likely that this was a joint enterprise, since the other instance of a double entry in the documents, also dated '20 novembre 1786' for some 'Heures nouvelles dédiées a la reine' also concerns the same two men. This suggests a partnership.
second_research_notes: Action completed - have gotten to bottom of this and attributed both editions to Le Seure while noting Monnoyer's involvement. Concluded they were in partnership on the editions.

notes: Edition verified by Worldcat and Dawson, after Martin et al., Bibliographie du genre romanesque français and permission copy.  Full edition title  and translation details after Worldcat. A 1786 Veuve Vivot 'Ange conducteur', nouvelle edition, is listed, but is said to be octavo (which could be large duodecimo), but since she produced many editions, and neither title nor format fit, this is assumed to be another edition. NB. The precise content of editions of the 'Ange conducteur' [and variant titles] evolved considerably over time and between editions: for practical purposes all variants have been treated as part of the same superbook [work] as clearly they belong to the same intellectual project.

full_book_title: Heures nouvelles dédiées à la reine
notes: Edition not located in Worldcat or by Dawson; superbook identified after Hovius edition. This entry was double counted by Dawson who also listed all four entries for this work under an 'anonymous' entry at his item 103. The double counting has been eliminated in this database. On this item the name of Monnoyeur pere in Neufchateau also appears in the source data, some of which appears to be added after it was first written. The relevant part of the entry  reads 'Le Seure l'aine, imp. a Nancy, Monnoyer Libre Imp [Libraire Imprimeur] a Neufchateau'. Dawson assumed that two licences were granted the same day, but it seems more likely that this was a joint enterprise, since the other instance of a double entry in the documents, also dated '20 novembre 1786' for some 'Heures dédiées au roi contenant les prières du matin, etc' also concerns the same two men. This sugggests a publishing partnership for both works.

Full title for edition and pagination are taken from these the digital copies. Dawson reports this edition after Danchin, noting the singular 'Amusement in the title' [cf. full_book_title: Recueil des oraisons funebres, prononcées par feu messire Jacques-Benigne Bossuet, Evêque de Meaux. Nouvelle édition, dans laquelle on a ajouté un précis de la vie de l'auteur. Recueil des oraisons funebres, prononcées par feu messire prononcées par messire Esprit Fléchier, evêque de Nîmes, Nouv. éd., dans laquelle on a ajouté un précis de la vie de l'auteur.
notes: Edition(s) verified in worldcat. It is not clear whether they were ever published as a single volume - usually they were issued separately and that is how they are found in library catalogues. The title 'Recueil des oraisons funebres' may have covered both, but the source data says that the collection was supposed to be one volume. The edition of Bossuet's 'Oraisons' contains the following: Éloge historique de feu messire Benigne Bossuet,, evêque de Meaux; Oraison funebre de la reine de la Grande-Bretagne; Oraison funebre de Henriette-Anne d'Angleterre, duchesse d'Orléans; Oraison funebre de Marie-Thérèse d'Autriche, infante d'Espagne, reine de France et de Navarre; Oraison funebre d'Anne de Gonzague de Cleves, princesse palatine; Oraison funebre de messire Michel Le Tellier, chancelier de France; Oraison funebre de Louis de Bourbon, prince de Condé. For the Flechier volume the oraisons are listed as Madame la duchesse de Montausier; Madame la duchesse d'Aiguillon; Monsieur de Turenne; Monsieur le premier président de Lamoignon; Marie Therese d'Autriche; Messire Michel Le Tellier; Madame la dauphine; Monsieur le duc de Montausier. The Imprint for Bossuet is given as: A Lyon, chez Faucheux, imprimeur-libraire quai & maison des Célestins. M. DCC. LXXX. Avec permission. 227-[1] p. ; in-12; for Flechier we have Lyon : Chez Faucheux, 1780. xxix, 226 pages. It appears that the two vols may have been published separately.

Secondary author: Le Maistre de Sacy, Louis Isaac
notes: Edition clearly was never published, or rather a new permit was issued in 1788. For this edition the words 'N'a pas' ( for N'a pas eu lieu') have been struck out of the register, whereas for the 1788 edition the register says 'donnée gratis n'ayant pas fait l'usage de la 1re'.

full_book_title: Nouveau (Le) Testament ... Traduit en françois sur la Vulgate. (L'Ordinaire de la Sainte Messe.)
Secondary author: Le Maistre de Sacy, Louis Isaac
notes: Edition verified through Worldcat after copy in the British Library. There can be little doubt that this is the correct edition, even though publisher not known to cataloguers from imprint, since the BL notice identifies the edition as 'Port Royal version'. Source data gives 'Nouveau testament en français, par Sacy': Sacy's translation of the Bible was known as the 'Bible de Port Royal'. A permit for Lallemant to produce this Bible had been granted in 1783 but expired before it was used: the register for the 1783 edition records 'N'a pas' ( for N'a pas eu lieu') but that was later struck out: the entry for the 1788 edition reveals that the new permit was 'donnée gratis n'ayant pas fait l'usage de la 1re'.

full_book_title: Pamela ou la vertu récompensée
Translator: La Chesnaye Des Bois, François Alexandre Aubert de
notes: Edition verified in Worldcat - edition details state '8 v.; 17 cm. (12mo)'; intriguingly Dawson also notes a (possibly pirate) Dusmenil and Poterne edition (1787) that contains the permission from 1781/2 for an edition of 1000. The genuine 1782 edition may be one of the editions that the STN traded (that described as 8 vols, in-12, Rouen, 1782), but not certain as there are no mentions of publisher. The STN bought copies from Jean Racine in 1784. There is also a 1781 edition 'A Rouen, chez Nicolas Labbey', but given that the permission was issued on 30 December and to Dumesnil and Labbey, it seems unlikely to be this edition.

full_book_title: Combat spirituel
notes: Edition not located. Superbook attribution not certain. Dawson assumes that all entries refer to Brignon's translation of Scupoli's 'Combat spirituel'. However, most entries under title 'Le Combat Spirituel' are grouped under a separate rubric in the source data four folios before those that can be positively linked to Brignon. However the two sets of entries form a single chronological series in the MS source data, which strongly supports his hypothesis. Nevertheless, it should be noted that other authors wrote works with similar titles. Source data gives model for this edition: 'Model Paris Price 24.'

full_book_title: Histoire des révolutions arrivées dans le gouvernement de la république romaine.
notes: Edition verified in Worldcat and by Dawson (subject to caveat it was not a piracy of the permit book). Catalogue note records that vol.2 contains a "Memoire envoyé d'Angleterre par Milord Stanhope, secrétaire d'état ... [sur différentes questions qui concernent la constitution du sénat de Rome]--Réponse [de Vertot] au Mémoire envoyé d'Angleterre à Paris", v. 2, p. [361]-382. This work may technically have been a piracy despite the permission, for most of Vertot's works came under a new 30 year privilege granted to Durand neveu on 2 June 1779: these included Vertot's Révolutions romaine (and Révolutions de Portugal and Révolutions de Suède). Worldcat details: 2 volumes ; 17 cm.

full_book_title: Histoire des révolutions romaines, par l'abbé de Vertot
notes: Edition was probably never published, as register is annotated 'N'a pas eu lieu'. Dawson suspects this was due to the granting of a 30 year privilege over several works including Vertot's Révolutions romaine (and Révolutions de Portugal and Révolutions de Suède) to Durand neveu on 2 June 1779. This probably explains the absence of these histories from the registers, and lack of post 1779 editions of the Révolutions romaine (though Laurent Dumesnil and two other publishers were granted permissions five months after the privilege.
